Option B (recommended): Use SSH (no tokens, no prompts)

Generate an SSH key (if you don’t already have one):

ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"


Press Enter through prompts (or set a passphrase).

Start ssh-agent and add the key:

eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519


Copy the public key and add it to GitHub:

cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub


GitHub → Settings → SSH and GPG keys → New SSH key

Test:

ssh -T git@github.com


Clone via SSH:

git clone git@github.com:teknozor/aiCompliance.git








ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -f ~/.ssh/aiCompliance_deploy -C "aiCompliance deploy key"

n2) Add the PUBLIC key as a Deploy Key in GitHub

On GitHub:

Repo → Settings

Deploy keys

Add new

Title: rhel-server-aiCompliance

Key: paste the content of:

cat ~/.ssh/aiCompliance_deploy.pub


✅ Leave “Allow write access” UNCHECKED (unless you need push)

Save

3) Configure SSH to use this key for this repo

Edit SSH config:

cat >> ~/.ssh/config <<'EOF'
Host github.com-aiCompliance
  HostName ssh.github.com
  Port 443
  User git
  IdentityFile ~/.ssh/aiCompliance_deploy
  IdentitiesOnly yes
EOF

chmod 600 ~/.ssh/config


(Using port 443 avoids your previous hanging issue.)

4) Clone using the deploy key
git clone github.com-aiCompliance:teknozor/aiCompliance.git

5) Test SSH explicitly (optional but useful)
ssh -T github.com-aiCompliance


Expected:

Hi! You've successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.

When SHOULD you check “Allow write access”?

Only if:

This server needs to push commits

Or tag releases

Or write back CI results

For installation / read-only usage → ❌ do not enable it

Why this is ideal for your case

✔ Works even if port 22 is blocked
✔ No GitHub password or token stored
✔ Least-privilege security
✔ Stable for servers & automation

If you want, I can:

Validate your ~/.ssh/config

Check permissions (ls -l ~/.ssh)

Or give you a one-command clone version
read -s -p "GitHub PAT: " TOKEN; echo
git clone https://github.com/teknozor/aiCompliance.git
unset TOKEN
